Wash and dry produce.

Halve, peel, and dice @yellow onion{1}. Thinly slice half the @jalapeño{1} into
rounds; mince remaining jalapeño. TIP: Remove ribs and seeds first for less
heat.

Heat a large drizzle of @cooking oil{2%tsp} in a #medium pot{} over
medium-high heat. Add onion and minced jalapeño; season with @salt{} and
@pepper{}. Cook, stirring, until softened, ~{5-7%minutes}.

Add @ground pork{10%oz}, @Mexican spice blend{1%tbsp}, and
@Southwest spice blend{1%tbsp} to #pot{}; season with salt and pepper. Cook,
breaking up meat into pieces, until browned and cooked through, ~{4-6%minutes}.

Stir @tomato paste{1.5%oz} into pot with pork mixture. Cook, stirring, until
dark red and combined, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Add @diced tomatoes{14%oz can}, @black beans{13.4%oz can} and their liquid,
@beef stock concentrate{1}, @water{1/4%cup}, salt, and pepper; stir to
combine. Bring to a simmer and cook, uncovered, until thickened,
~{8-10%minutes}. Turn off heat. Taste and season with salt and pepper.

Divide chili between #bowls{}. Top with @Monterey Jack cheese{1/4%cup},
@sour cream{2%tbsp}, and as much sliced jalapeño as you like. Serve.

> A good chili has well-seasoned meat, creamy beans, and tender vegetables.
> A great chili comes together in one pot in under an hour. This chili is one
> of the greats. And once you take a bite, we can guarantee you'll agree.

> If you've got some on hand, why not crumble up some tortilla chips and
> sprinkle them on top for a crunch?